==Geography==
[[File:Athene-sat.JPG|thumb|View of the ''Attica Basin'' from space.]]

Athens sprawls across the central plain of [[Attica]] that is often referred to as the ''Attica or Athens Basin''. The basin is bound by four large mountains; Mount [[Egaleo|Aegaleo]] to the west, Mount [[Parnitha]] to the north, Mount [[Penteli, Greece|Penteli]] to the northeast and Mount [[Hymettus]] to the east of the Athens Metropolitan Area&lt;ref name=&quot;Focus on Athens&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.urbanheatisland.info/images/newsletter/UHI_newsletter_Issue_1.pdf | title=Focus on Athens| accessdate=18 March 2011 | work=UHI Quarterly Newsletter, Issue 1, May 2009, page 2|publisher=www.urbanheatisland.info}}&lt;/ref&gt; and also the extension of the Athens basin is the [[Thriasian plain]] west of the capital. The [[Saronic Gulf]] lies in the southwest. Mount Parnitha is the tallest of the four mountains ({{convert|1413|m|ft|0|abbr=on}})&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.parnitha-np.gr/welcome.htm |title=Welcome!!! |publisher=Parnitha-np.gr |accessdate=10 June 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; and it has been declared a [[national park]].

Athens is built around a number of hills. [[Mount Lycabettus|Lycabettus]] is one of the tallest hills of the city proper and provides a view of the entire Attica Basin. The geomorphology of Athens is deemed to be one of the most complex in the world due to its mountains and causes a [[inversion (meteorology)|temperature inversion]] phenomenon which, along with the failure of the Greek Government to control industrial pollution, is responsible for the air pollution problems the city has recently faced.&lt;ref name=tung/&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.minenv.gr/1/12/122/12204/e1220400.html |work=Hellenic Ministry of the Environment and Public Works |title=Daily Report on Air Pollution Levels |accessdate=26 January 2007 |publisher=www.minenv.gr}}&lt;/ref&gt; ([[Los Angeles]] and [[Mexico City]] also suffer with similar geomorphology inversion problems).&lt;ref name=tung&gt;{{cite book |last=Tung |first=Anthony |chapter=The City the Gods Besieged |title=Preserving the World's Great Cities: The Destruction and Renewal of the Historic Metropolis |year=2001 |location=New York |publisher=Three Rivers Press |isbn=0-609-80815-X |page=266}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==Climate==

The Athens region enjoys a [[Mediterranean climate]] ([[Köppen climate classification|Köppen]] ''Csa'') with typically warm summers and mild winters. 

With an average of 414.1&amp;nbsp;mm of yearly precipitation, rainfall occurs largely between October and April. July and August are the driest months, with typically one or two sparse thunderstorms a month. 

[[Parnitha|Mount Parnitha]] acts as a rainshadow for the city, as a result of which precipitation is typically lower than other parts of the country.

Athens is perhaps Europe's warmest [[capital city]] during the summer months, surpassed only by a handful of large European cities such as [[Córdoba, Spain|Córdoba]] and [[Seville]]. Daily average highs for July have been measured at {{convert|33.5|C|1}} at [[Nea Filalelfia]] weather station, but other parts of the cities may be even warmer. Temperatures often surpass  {{convert|38|°C|°F|0}} during the city's notorious heatwaves.&lt;ref name=&quot;Focus on Athens&quot;/&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://esciencenews.com/articles/2009/08/29/esa.helps.make.summer.city.more.bearable|title=European Space Agency to help Athens become bearable in summer |accessdate=17 April 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; 
 
Winters are mild and rainy, with a January average of {{convert|8.9|C|1}}; in Nea Filadelfia and {{convert|10.3|C|1}} in Hellenikon; 

Snowstorms are infrequent but can cause significant disruption when they occur.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-12674491 visited may 6, 2011]&lt;/ref&gt;

Below are the meteorological data for the northern suburb of Nea Filadelfeia

