'''Ames''' is a city located in the central part of the U.S. state of [[Iowa]] in [[Story County]], and approximately {{convert|30|mi|km}} north of [[Des Moines, Iowa|Des Moines]]. It is the principal city of the Ames, Iowa
[[Metropolitan Statistical Area]] which encompasses all of Story County, and which, when combined with the Boone, Iowa [[Micropolitan Statistical Area]], comprises the larger [[Ames-Boone, IA CSA|Ames-Boone]] [[Combined Statistical Area]]. As of the [[2010 United States Census|2010 Census]], the city population was 58,965.  While Ames is the largest city in Story County, the county seat is in [[Nevada, Iowa|Nevada]] which is {{convert|8|mi|km}} east of Ames.

Ames is the home of [[Iowa State University|Iowa State University of Science and Technology]] (ISU), a public research institution with leading [[Agriculture]], [[Design]], [[Engineering]], and [[Iowa State University College of Veterinary Medicine|Veterinary Medicine]] colleges.  [[Iowa State University|ISU]] is the nation's first designated [[land-grant university]],&lt;ref name=&quot;lib.iastate.edu&quot;&gt;[http://www.lib.iastate.edu/spcl/exhibits/150/template/timeline-1858.html Iowa State University Time Line, 1858–1874]. Iowa State University Website.&lt;/ref&gt;	and the birthplace of the [[Atanasoff-Berry Computer]], the world's first electronic digital computer.&lt;ref&gt;''The First Electronic Computer'' by Arthur W. Burks&lt;/ref&gt; Ames hosts one of two national sites for the USDA's Animal and Plant Health and Inspection Service (APHIS) which comprises the National Veterinary Services Laboratories (NVSL) and the Center for Veterinary Biologics (CVB).&lt;ref&gt;http://www.aphis.usda.gov/animal_health/lab_info_services&lt;/ref&gt;  Ames is also the home of the USDA's Agricultural Research Service's National Animal Disease Center (NADC).&lt;ref&gt;http://ars.usda.gov/main/site_main.htm?modecode=36-25-30-00&lt;/ref&gt;  NADC is the largest federal animal disease center in the U.S., conducting research aimed at solving animal health and food safety problems faced by livestock producers and the public. Ames has the headquarters for the [[Iowa Department of Transportation]].

In 2010 Ames was ranked #9 on CNNMoney.com Best Places to Live list.
&lt;ref name=&quot;CNNMoney.com&quot;&gt;{{cite news| url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/moneymag/bplive/2010/snapshots/PL1901855.html | work=CNN | title=Best Places to Live 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;

It is the site of the [[Ames Straw Poll]], an important [[straw poll]] in the [[United States Republican Party|Republican party]] presidential nomination process as well as the first in the nation Democratic and Republican caucuses (''see Politics, below'').

==History==
The city was founded in 1864 as a station stop on the [[Cedar Rapids and Missouri Railroad]] and was named after 19th century [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Congressman]] [[Oakes Ames]] of [[Massachusetts]], who was influential in the building of the [[First transcontinental railroad (North America)|transcontinental railroad]]. Ames was founded near a location that was deemed favorable for a railroad crossing of the [[Skunk River]].

==Geography==
According to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|21.6|sqmi|1}}, of which {{convert|21.6|sqmi|1}} is land and {{convert|0.04|sqmi|1}} (0.09%) is water.

Ames is located on [[Interstate 35]], [[U.S. Route 30]] &amp; [[U.S. Route 69|69]], and the cross country line of the [[Union Pacific Railroad]], located roughly {{convert|30|mi}} north of the state capital [[Des Moines, Iowa|Des Moines]]. Two small rivers run through the town, the [[Skunk River|South Skunk River]] and [[Squaw Creek (Ames, Iowa)|Squaw Creek]].

=== Neighborhoods ===
Ames is made up of several distinct neighborhoods, including Allenview, Bentwood, Bloomington Heights, Broadmoor, [[Campustown, Ames|Campustown]], College Heights, College Park, Country Gables, Dauntless, Dayton Park, East Hickory Park, Gateway Green Hills, Gateway Hills, Hillside, [[Iowa State University]], Little Hollywood, Main Street Cultural District (Downtown Ames), Melrose Park, Northridge Heights, Northridge Parkway, Old Town Historic Preservation District, Ontario Heights, Parkview Heights, Ridgewood, Riggenberg Park, Skycrest, Somerset, South Fork, South Gateway, Spring Valley, Stone Brooke, Sunset Ridge, and West Ames.

==== Campustown ====
[[Image:LEEDZ.jpg|thumb|left|&lt;center&gt;Leedzsalon in Campustown&lt;/center&gt;]]
[[Image:Be.café.jpg|thumb|&lt;center&gt;Café Beaudelaire in Campustown&lt;/center&gt;]]
{{Expand section|date=November 2010}}
Campustown is the neighborhood directly south of Iowa State University Central Campus bordered by [[Lincoln Way]] on the north. Campustown is a high-density mixed-use neighborhood that is home to many student apartments, nightlife venues, restaurants, and numerous other establishments, most of which are unique to Ames.{{-}} &lt;!--FYI this template makes the next section drop below pictures--&gt;

=== Climate ===
Ames has a [[humid continental climate]] ([[Köppen climate classification]] ''Dfa'').

